WEBVTT

00:05.539 --> 00:06.373
GWEN IFILL: Good
evening. I'm Gwen Ifill.

00:06.373 --> 00:08.575
JUDY WOODRUFF: And
I'm Judy Woodruff.

00:08.575 --> 00:13.881
GWEN IFILL: On the "NewsHour"
tonight: Donald Trump defends
his record on women, as Hillary

00:13.881 --> 00:18.385
Clinton wades into the fray.
Surveying the week ahead in
politics.

00:18.385 --> 00:22.623
JUDY WOODRUFF: Then: protests
and a state of emergency again
in Saint Louis and Ferguson,

00:22.623 --> 00:24.491
Missouri.

00:24.491 --> 00:29.997
GWEN IFILL: A pious nation
resists family planning efforts
to address poverty, political

00:29.997 --> 00:33.934
pushback to providing free
contraceptives in the
Philippines.

00:33.934 --> 00:37.938
JUDY WOODRUFF: Plus, a doctor
recounts his struggle for
survival after contracting
Ebola.

00:44.344 --> 00:49.549
to get Ebola, we're all going to
die. In West Africa, the fear
presented itself as

00:49.549 --> 00:52.819
denial that Ebola was even real.

00:52.819 --> 00:58.825
GWEN IFILL: All that and more
on tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

00:58.825 --> 01:02.596
(BREAK)

01:02.596 --> 01:13.140
JUDY WOODRUFF: This was a day
of bombings and bloodshed in
three major countries across

01:13.140 --> 01:19.746
the Muslim world. In Iraq,
Islamic State suicide bombers
killed nearly 60 people and

01:19.746 --> 01:24.117
wounded more 100 others. The
attackers struck after nightfall
in Diyala province, just over

01:24.117 --> 01:27.020
30 miles northeast of Baghdad.

01:27.020 --> 01:32.392
GWEN IFILL: And in Afghanistan,
Taliban suicide bombers struck
again, killing at least

01:32.392 --> 01:37.631
five people and wounding 16
outside Kabul's international
airport. The blast at a busy

01:37.631 --> 01:41.868
roundabout followed Friday's
attacks that killed nearly 50.

01:41.868 --> 01:45.605
And the Afghan president
demanded a crackdown today on
Taliban elements based in
neighboring

01:45.605 --> 01:47.841
Pakistan.

01:47.841 --> 01:54.881
ASHRAF GHANI, President of
Afghanistan (through
translator): If Pakistan
doesn't have the

01:54.881 --> 01:59.553
capacity to bring them to the
table, they have this capacity
to stop their activities,

01:59.553 --> 02:03.023
to close their offices, to bring
the insurgents to justice, and
to not allow their wounded

02:03.023 --> 02:05.592
to be treated in the hospital.

02:05.592 --> 02:09.029
GWEN IFILL: President Ghani
also spoke by phone with
Secretary of State John Kerry to

02:09.029 --> 02:11.865
express his concern.

02:11.865 --> 02:17.304
JUDY WOODRUFF: The U.S.
Consulate in Istanbul, Turkey,
came under fire today as attacks
rocked

02:17.304 --> 02:23.410
that country. Investigators
said two women belonging to a
far-left radical group shot

02:23.410 --> 02:26.913
at the consulate. Witnesses
said police wounded one of the
attackers after she refused

02:26.913 --> 02:30.217
to surrender.

02:30.217 --> 02:38.492
MAN (through translator): It
was about 6:30 in the morning.
We heard the sound of gunfire.

02:38.492 --> 02:42.929
The woman and the police officer
started clashing. I guess the
woman was an amateur

02:42.929 --> 02:46.333
because she had dropped her
ammunition clip. She was
throwing what looked like
stones.

02:46.333 --> 02:49.503
The officer shouted at her once
or two times, "Lay down, lay
down."

02:49.503 --> 02:55.342
JUDY WOODRUFF: No one else was
hurt there, but three militants
and two policemen died

02:55.342 --> 03:01.181
in a car bombing and gun battle
at a police station in Istanbul.
Elsewhere, a roadside

03:01.181 --> 03:05.685
bomb killed four Turkish police
officers. It all came amid a
government crackdown

03:05.685 --> 03:10.290
on Islamic State, Kurdish
elements and far-left militants.

03:10.290 --> 03:15.529
GWEN IFILL: Migrants fleeing
conflict in Syria and
Afghanistan arrived by the
hundreds

03:15.529 --> 03:21.501
in Greece this weekend. Coast
Guard vessels rescued more than
1,400 people in dozens of

03:21.501 --> 03:26.173
operations. Meanwhile, a
policeman on Kos Island pulled a
knife and struck migrants

03:26.173 --> 03:30.710
as tempers flared in a crowd
waiting for immigration papers.

03:30.710 --> 03:35.849
JUDY WOODRUFF: Back in this
country, the governor of
Colorado declared a disaster
today

03:35.849 --> 03:40.921
after a major toxic spill, this
as word came that the disaster
is far worse than it first

03:40.921 --> 03:44.624
appeared.

03:44.624 --> 03:50.397
The Environmental Protection
Agency has now confirmed the
spill totals three million
gallons,

03:50.397 --> 03:56.570
three times larger than
initially estimated. The mix of
heavy metals, including arsenic

03:56.570 --> 04:01.908
and lead, has transformed the
Animas River into
mustard-colored soup.

04:01.908 --> 04:04.878
MAN: It's definitely not how
the river is supposed to look.
It's already hard enough

04:04.878 --> 04:07.547
to catch fish in the Animas, and
you know this stuff, it's
definitely not good for them,

04:07.547 --> 04:10.050
going to kill a lot
of these fish off.

04:10.050 --> 04:15.088
JUDY WOODRUFF: It started
Wednesday, when an EPA team
accidentally released
contaminated

04:15.088 --> 04:21.795
water from the abandoned Gold
King Mine north of Silverton,
Colorado. It spewed into the

04:21.795 --> 04:28.235
Animas and headed downstream.
The tainted torrent has now
traveled south more than 100

04:28.235 --> 04:33.974
miles, flowing into New Mexico,
where the Animas meets the San
Juan River.

04:33.974 --> 04:38.378
New Mexico's governor, Susana
Martinez, yesterday got an
aerial view of the contamination
in

04:38.378 --> 04:39.913
Farmington.

04:39.913 --> 04:43.517
GOV. SUSANA MARTINEZ (R), New
Mexico: You can't even describe
it. It's like when I

04:43.517 --> 04:48.889
flew over the fires. And you
see something that your mind
isn't ready or adjusted to

04:48.889 --> 04:50.724
see.

04:50.724 --> 04:57.164
JUDY WOODRUFF: The EPA says it
doesn't expect a major effect on
wildlife. And because

04:57.164 --> 05:02.869
utilities closed their intake
valves, there's no sign that
drinking water has been
contaminated.

05:02.869 --> 05:06.907
Still, homeowners like
Rosemary Hart are frustrated.

05:06.907 --> 05:11.211
ROSEMARY HART, Homeowner: I'm
here on my property, and I
cannot shower. I cannot

05:11.211 --> 05:15.515
cook. I cannot do anything with
the water from my water well.

05:15.515 --> 05:20.820
JUDY WOODRUFF: Adding to the
frustration, it took the EPA a
full day to notify communities

05:20.820 --> 05:28.061
of the spill. Now the yellow
flow is heading west toward Lake
Powell in Utah, a popular

05:28.061 --> 05:33.733
tourist destination, and EPA
officials have yet to indicate
how long cleanup will take.

05:39.139 --> 05:41.308
the spill.

05:41.308 --> 05:45.712
GWEN IFILL: Billionaire
investor Warren Buffett
announced his company's biggest
deal

05:45.712 --> 05:50.850
ever today. Berkshire Hathaway
will buy Precision Castparts, an
aerospace and industrial

05:50.850 --> 05:54.721
company, for $37 billion.

05:54.721 --> 05:59.759
That news, plus a rise in oil
prices, sent Wall Street
surging. The Dow Jones
industrial

05:59.759 --> 06:05.632
average gained more than 240
points to close above 17600.
The Nasdaq rose 58 points,

06:05.632 --> 06:09.903
and the S&P 500 added 26.

06:09.903 --> 06:15.375
JUDY WOODRUFF: And Google will
become part of a new holding
company known as Alphabet.

06:15.375 --> 06:20.847
The search giant unveiled the
change in operating structure
after the markets closed.

06:20.847 --> 06:24.417
The switch will take place later
this year, and Google's stock
will automatically be converted

06:24.417 --> 06:28.355
to Alphabet stock.

06:28.355 --> 06:32.759
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
the week ahead in politics with
Tamara Keith and Susan

06:32.759 --> 06:44.104
Page; protests and a state of
emergency called again in
Ferguson, plus much more.

06:44.104 --> 07:03.757
GWEN IFILL: Donald Trump
continues to consume the
post-debate debate, Hillary
Clinton lashes

07:03.757 --> 07:08.328
out at the Republicans, and
Bernie Sanders draws huge West
Coast crowds.

07:08.328 --> 07:13.133
You may have heard Trump sparked
an uproar when he described FOX
News moderator Megyn

07:13.133 --> 07:18.238
Kelly as having "blood coming
out of her eyes, blood coming
out of her wherever." She was

07:18.238 --> 07:21.041
-- he said, "In my opinion,
she was off-base."

07:21.041 --> 07:25.412
The next day, he said he meant
blood coming out of her nose.

07:25.412 --> 07:29.149
Today, Hillary Clinton,
campaigning in New Hampshire,
said Trump was outrageous, but

07:29.149 --> 07:33.687
that Republicans who oppose all
abortions are just as bad.

07:33.687 --> 07:36.890
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON (D),
Presidential Candidate: While
what Donald Trump said about
Megyn

07:36.890 --> 07:42.796
Kelly is outrageous, what the
rest of the Republicans are
saying about all women is

07:42.796 --> 07:49.202
also outrageous. They brag
about slashing women's health
care funding. They say they

07:49.202 --> 07:54.040
would force women who have been
raped to carry their rapist's
child.

07:54.040 --> 07:58.378
GWEN IFILL: Sounds like a
perfect time for a Politics
Monday.

07:58.378 --> 08:01.314
We're joined from New Hampshire
tonight by Tamara Keith of NPR,
and here in the studio

08:01.314 --> 08:04.451
by Susan Page of USA Today.

08:04.451 --> 08:09.823
Tamara, you were in New
Hampshire with Hillary covering
Hillary Clinton today. Tell us

08:09.823 --> 08:14.227
a little bit about this whole
idea, this broad idea of women's
issues. So far, we're talking

08:14.227 --> 08:19.666
about the slur was that Donald
Trump did or didn't intend.
We're talking about abortion,

08:19.666 --> 08:22.635
but women's issues, it seems to
me, especially when it comes to
an unknown candidate like

08:22.635 --> 08:24.738
Donald Trump, is much
broader than that.

08:24.738 --> 08:28.375
TAMARA KEITH, National
Public Radio: Certainly.

08:28.375 --> 08:33.580
And Donald Trump, over the
weekend, said that he's huge on
women's issues. It's not
entirely

08:33.580 --> 08:40.820
clear what that means. Trump,
before he was pro-life, was
pro-choice. And, of course,

08:40.820 --> 08:45.058
that's one of many issues where
there are lots of substantive
questions that could be

08:45.058 --> 08:49.496
asked of a candidate, but,
typically, he spends a lot of
time feuding instead.

08:49.496 --> 08:54.601
GWEN IFILL: Has the Clinton
campaign decided this is an
opportunity for them?

08:54.601 --> 08:59.939
TAMARA KEITH: Oh, absolutely.
Hillary Clinton was having a lot
of fun in that media

08:59.939 --> 09:03.910
availability today, though --
and you also got the sense that
she would have been perfectly

09:03.910 --> 09:08.515
happy if someone, anyone, had
asked her a detailed policy
question about her college

09:08.515 --> 09:11.785
affordability plan, which
is what she was there for.

09:11.785 --> 09:16.656
But, clearly, Clinton is using
this to go after the Republican
field as a whole, to

09:16.656 --> 09:21.828
tie them to Donald Trump, and
also, in particular, today, she
was talking about Marco Rubio.

09:21.828 --> 09:27.100
That's the Florida senator who
many say performed quite well in
that debate last week,

09:27.100 --> 09:36.176
and she was talking about his
position on abortion to not
include incest or rape, and

09:36.176 --> 09:40.980
making the argument that that
was the more extreme position
than any of the entertaining

09:40.980 --> 09:44.851
things that Donald Trump said.
And she described him as an
entertainer.

09:44.851 --> 09:48.588
GWEN IFILL: OK, Susan, let's
talk about Donald Trump. It's
-- we have to. He's

09:48.588 --> 09:51.524
still leading the polls. He
doesn't appeared to have been
hurt at all by whatever happened

09:51.524 --> 09:55.195
in that debate or people's
interpretations of it.

09:55.195 --> 09:58.965
But when we talk about Donald
Trump and we talk about where he
stands on issues, we know

09:58.965 --> 10:01.034
about the things he says. What
does he believe, especially when
it comes to these issues?

10:05.238 --> 10:08.374
who has ever served in public
office, so there's no voting
record that we can go look at,
as

10:08.374 --> 10:12.111
we can with people who served
as governors and senators.

10:12.111 --> 10:16.749
And, in fact, if you go on
DonaldJTrump.com, his Web site,
as I did just before we came

10:16.749 --> 10:20.887
on board, there are ways to buy
T-shirts with Trump's name,
there are a lot of news stories

10:20.887 --> 10:24.657
posted about how well he's doing
in the polls, you can contribute
to his campaign, but there

10:24.657 --> 10:29.596
is not even a tab that takes you
to his policy positions on
issues.

10:29.596 --> 10:32.499
There's nothing on his Web site
up to this point that explains
where he stands on issues

10:32.499 --> 10:36.369
like education, or health care,
or jobs or terrorism. These are
all issues that of

10:36.369 --> 10:39.372
course women care
about, as do men.

10:39.372 --> 10:41.774
GWEN IFILL: Well, that's the
thing. We're talking about --
when we say women's issues,

10:41.774 --> 10:45.512
we're also talking about health
care and education and college
affordability.

10:45.512 --> 10:48.548
But we have heard nothing
from him on any of that.

10:48.548 --> 10:51.017
SUSAN PAGE: And you know what?
I think, for his core
supporters, it doesn't matter.

10:51.017 --> 10:55.822
They're endorsing kind of an
attitude that has served him
well so far.

10:55.822 --> 11:00.159
But if he wants to grow his
support, if he wants to become
somebody who is actually taken

11:00.159 --> 11:02.929
seriously as a potential
nominee, he's going to have to
take positions on some of these

11:02.929 --> 11:05.131
big issues.

11:05.131 --> 11:08.234
GWEN IFILL: Tamara, we saw how
Hillary Clinton has been
responding to this. How about
the

11:08.234 --> 11:11.804
others, especially all the
Republican candidates? How have
they been responding? They have

11:11.804 --> 11:16.209
obviously been trying to fight
to get themselves heard in all
of this.

11:16.209 --> 11:20.847
TAMARA KEITH: Yes, any number
of candidates have said things
like, well, don't you just

11:20.847 --> 11:27.086
want to ask me about what I want
to do, John Kasich being one of
them. Senator Lindsey

11:27.086 --> 11:33.092
Graham of South Carolina came
out with another strongly-worded
statement saying, come on,

11:33.092 --> 11:36.896
let's just ditch this guy,
basically, more or less.

11:36.896 --> 11:42.735
And I think what's going on
here, what's interesting though
is that Donald Trump keeps going
from

11:42.735 --> 11:47.974
feud to feud to feud. He said
mean things about Megyn Kelly.
Then he moved on and

11:47.974 --> 11:52.612
said mean things about Carly
Fiorina, one of the other
presidential candidates, and

11:52.612 --> 11:58.585
he keeps doing that, keeps
sparking these feuds. It's kind
of like rap feuds of the

11:58.585 --> 12:04.591
'90s, where they're feuding and
actually the feud gives
everybody more publicity. So

12:04.591 --> 12:08.828
some candidates are embracing
the fight with Trump.

12:08.828 --> 12:13.333
GWEN IFILL: It's true. I have
been following this feud between
Meek Mill and Drake over

12:13.333 --> 12:16.202
the last week. I have no idea
what it's about, but I know it's
a beef.

12:16.202 --> 12:20.073
OK. So, we have the same thing
happening here. But here's what
I'm curious about,

12:20.073 --> 12:25.044
Susan. There's power in this,
isn't there? He was mad at FOX
News, but now it appears

12:25.044 --> 12:29.215
he's going to appear on FOX News
because he made up with Roger
Ailes.

12:29.215 --> 12:32.552
SUSAN PAGE: So, here's the
amazing thing. Not only does he
lead in the polls, but

12:32.552 --> 12:35.989
Donald Trump is defining
the entire conversation.

12:35.989 --> 12:41.327
So the other nominees, the other
candidates either try to get
into the story, like Rand

12:41.327 --> 12:45.264
Paul criticizing him as not
really a real conservative or
Bobby Jindal saying that he's

12:45.264 --> 12:48.067
going to just say Trump's name
randomly through his speeches in
an effort to get attention,

12:48.067 --> 12:51.204
or they're trying to figure out
how to talk about something
else.

12:51.204 --> 12:55.541
That's what you see with Marco
Rubio and John Kasich, where
they are really desperate to

12:55.541 --> 12:59.512
try to break through on the
issues that they want to talk
about and avoid having to
respond

12:59.512 --> 13:03.816
every day in every way to
outrageous comments by Donald
Trump. And I don't think that

13:03.816 --> 13:07.587
they have quite figured out how
to do that at the moment,
because Donald Trump is still,

13:07.587 --> 13:10.857
as he likes to be,
right at center stage.

13:10.857 --> 13:15.395
GWEN IFILL: OK, Tamara, let's
talk about Bernie Sanders. He
was on a West Coast swing

13:15.395 --> 13:20.366
this week and he attracted tens
of thousands of people to his
rallies in Seattle, in Portland,

13:20.366 --> 13:24.337
Oregon. And he's on his
way to Los Angeles today.

13:24.337 --> 13:28.007
Is this something -- first of
all, what is the appeal for
Bernie Sanders? Why is he

13:28.007 --> 13:31.277
getting these massive crowds at
this time, in August, for
heaven's sakes? And what

13:31.277 --> 13:34.180
are the Hillary Clinton
people thinking about this?

13:34.180 --> 13:39.419
TAMARA KEITH: Well, and, also,
he was endorsed today by the
nurses union. That's what he

13:39.419 --> 13:43.256
was doing in L.A., was picking
up this big national
endorsement.

13:43.256 --> 13:49.862
So Bernie Sanders has captured
something. He's really captured
a desire among many

13:49.862 --> 13:54.534
people to fix income inequality.
He's talking about college
affordability. He has been

13:54.534 --> 14:02.141
talking about that for months.
He really, in stark terms,
spells out the feeling that

14:02.141 --> 14:06.379
a lot of people have that it's
just harder to get ahead, and
that's what he's capturing,

14:06.379 --> 14:09.315
and people are showing
up to see him.

14:09.315 --> 14:13.886
Now, I can't tell you what
portion of the people in those
arenas are just there to say,

14:13.886 --> 14:18.958
hey, who is this guy and how
many of them would go out and,
say, caucus for him in Iowa

14:18.958 --> 14:24.263
or volunteer for his campaign.
It's not clear to me what the
share is in those people

14:24.263 --> 14:26.399
that are showing up.

14:26.399 --> 14:27.734
GWEN IFILL: That's the same
question that could be asked
about Donald Trump at this

14:27.734 --> 14:30.002
stage.

14:30.002 --> 14:33.539
But what I'm curious about,
Susan, also is whether the
Hillary Clinton people are
worried

14:33.539 --> 14:35.842
about it. She was asked about
it today and she just said, oh,
he's a nice colleague.

14:35.842 --> 14:38.945
She didn't have anything
negative to say about him.

14:38.945 --> 14:42.482
SUSAN PAGE: There is no
percentage for Hillary Clinton
to attack Bernie Sanders.

14:42.482 --> 14:45.384
There's every -- because
everything she wants to do is to
get Bernie Sanders supporters

14:45.384 --> 14:49.388
to support her either now or
later. She's really focused her
fire on the people she

14:49.388 --> 14:54.794
thinks will be her potential
opponents, Jeb Bush and today
Marco Rubio.

14:54.794 --> 14:59.465
But, certainly, Bernie Sanders
is underscoring some of the
vulnerabilities that Hillary
Clinton

14:59.465 --> 15:03.035
has. I don't think the Hillary
Clinton thinks he's going to
take the nomination, but when

15:03.035 --> 15:09.008
he gets 28,000 people to come to
a rally in Portland, Oregon, it
underscored -- could

15:09.008 --> 15:12.945
she get 20,000 people to come
there with no organization, with
no money for ads, with

15:12.945 --> 15:15.348
no infrastructure?

15:15.348 --> 15:20.653
So I think he's concerning in
that way, not so much that he
takes the nomination, but

15:20.653 --> 15:24.724
he shows the kind of energy
that she has yet to show.

15:24.724 --> 15:29.028
GWEN IFILL: You begin to wonder
if, at this stage of the
campaign, what we're really
watching

15:29.028 --> 15:34.033
for is the cumulative effect of
either the negative or e-mail
questions which don't go

15:34.033 --> 15:37.470
away, of the outrage from Trump
or even just the crowds building
on themselves for Bernie

15:37.470 --> 15:39.338
Sanders. Maybe
that's where we are.

15:39.338 --> 15:40.106
SUSAN PAGE: And, of course,
we're pretty far away from the
election.

15:40.106 --> 15:42.275
GWEN IFILL: No, we are?

15:42.275 --> 15:42.809
SUSAN PAGE: Yes, we are. We
are going to be talking about
this for a long time.

15:48.915 --> 15:52.318
is going to be, who has got
strengths and weaknesses and how
they might play out. But,

15:52.318 --> 15:55.621
a year from now, we will still
be talking about some of these
same characters.

15:55.621 --> 15:57.857
GWEN IFILL: And a year from
now, Tamara Keith will probably
still be in New Hampshire,

15:57.857 --> 15:59.659
but maybe we will see you
here this next week.

15:59.659 --> 16:00.993
TAMARA KEITH: Maybe.

16:00.993 --> 16:04.330
GWEN IFILL: Tamara Keith of
NPR, Susan Page with USA Today,
thank you both.

16:04.330 --> 16:14.707
SUSAN PAGE: Thank you.

