LORETTA LYNCH, U.S. Attorney
General: I strongly condemn the
violence that was perpetrated

16:58.517 --> 17:06.259
against the community, including
the police officers, in Ferguson
last evening. Not

17:06.259 --> 17:13.132
only does violence obscure any
message of peaceful protest. It
places the community

17:13.132 --> 17:19.038
as well as the officers who are
seeking to protect it in harm's
way.

17:19.038 --> 17:24.043
JUDY WOODRUFF: There were new
protests around Ferguson and
Saint Louis today. Some 100

17:24.043 --> 17:28.648
people rallied at the county
courthouse. Nearly 60 were
arrested.

17:28.648 --> 17:33.219
I spoke a short time ago with
reporter Yamiche Alcindor, who's
covering the story for USA

17:33.219 --> 17:34.654
Today.

17:34.654 --> 17:36.923
Yamiche, welcome.

17:36.923 --> 17:39.725
What is the situation right now?

17:39.725 --> 17:42.962
YAMICHE ALCINDOR, USA Today:
Well, moments ago, several
protesters were arrested outside

17:42.962 --> 17:46.365
a federal courthouse building.

17:46.365 --> 17:51.270
And some of them are really
people that are really prominent
protesters, along with Cornel

17:51.270 --> 17:54.473
West. So, right now, they're
being processed at that federal
courthouse and they're actually

17:54.473 --> 17:59.312
facing federal charges. But
it's going to be really a $125
fine. They wouldn't really

17:59.312 --> 18:03.749
say whether or not it's a
misdemeanor or a felony, but of
course it's a $125 fine.

18:03.749 --> 18:07.286
So, it's not -- it's still a
summons. It's not going to be
anything too serious, but

18:07.286 --> 18:11.123
this is still part of the Moral
Monday that people had here
today, where it was really

18:11.123 --> 18:15.261
a series of civil disobediences
that they wanted to have in
coordination and really

18:15.261 --> 18:17.563
in memory of Michael Brown.

18:17.563 --> 18:21.067
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, this was
planned before any of this
violence last night? Is that

18:21.067 --> 18:23.035
right?

18:23.035 --> 18:25.538
YAMICHE ALCINDOR: Yes, before
any of the violence that
happened last night, before

18:25.538 --> 18:29.375
any of the looting, before the
second police-involved shooting.

18:29.375 --> 18:33.646
There are people that had
already planned to have acts of
civil disobedience. They

18:33.646 --> 18:37.950
were thinking about the idea
that, after Michael Brown's,
several people, hundreds of
people

18:37.950 --> 18:42.188
took to the streets protesting
and demonstrating, mostly
peacefully. But also of course
we

18:42.188 --> 18:45.658
remember that burned QuikTrip
that really put this whole story
on the nation's spotlight.

18:51.931 --> 18:55.868
Louis, there were several actual
acts of disobedience, but the
one that I attended today was at
the

18:55.868 --> 18:58.971
federal courthouse where several
members of the clergy got
together and were purposefully

18:58.971 --> 19:00.706
arrested.

19:00.706 --> 19:04.643
JUDY WOODRUFF: And now we know
there is a state of emergency
that has been declared

19:04.643 --> 19:08.080
in the area as a
result of last night.

19:08.080 --> 19:11.717
But take us back to yesterday.
This was supposed to be a day --
in fact, it was a

19:11.717 --> 19:15.521
day of peaceful protest in
memory of Michael Brown. But
then what happened last night?

19:19.859 --> 19:23.829
night in Ferguson
when things get bad.

19:23.829 --> 19:27.466
Usually, what happens in
Ferguson, if there is going to
be violence, because I should

19:27.466 --> 19:30.669
say that there usually isn't
violence in Ferguson -- I have
been here several months -- but

19:30.669 --> 19:33.506
when there is violence, what
happens is that you get to a
point in the night where you

19:33.506 --> 19:37.610
think, OK, it's time to -- I can
go home, the crowd is kind of
dispersing.

19:37.610 --> 19:41.447
And then, out of nowhere, that's
what happened last night. There
was a line of police officers,

19:41.447 --> 19:44.483
protesters yelling at them, and
then after a while, it kind of
just lulled and people

19:44.483 --> 19:48.387
were kind of wandering around.
I myself was thinking about
getting into my car. And

19:48.387 --> 19:51.690
then we just heard a barrage of
gunshots. It was really the
most terrifying moments

19:51.690 --> 19:54.627
of my journalistic career.

19:54.627 --> 19:59.265
I ducked and was trying to run
behind cars. Dozens of police
officers were also cowering

19:59.265 --> 20:03.803
behind their cars. You know the
situation is really important
and really dangerous when

20:03.803 --> 20:08.507
the police are also running and
taking fire. And we later
learned that a young man was

20:08.507 --> 20:12.545
shot, and that it was a
police-involved shooting. The
police say there was one --
there was

20:12.545 --> 20:14.447
at first a group of two people
shooting and then one of the
people that were shooting

20:14.447 --> 20:16.549
ran away.

20:16.549 --> 20:20.419
They're calling him a suspect.
And that man ran away. And when
police spotted him,

20:20.419 --> 20:24.824
he started again firing at the
police. That's what police say.
And then they also returned

20:24.824 --> 20:27.193
fire and this young
man was shot.

20:27.193 --> 20:30.563
JUDY WOODRUFF: So there clearly
seem to be two sides to the
story. The young man's

20:30.563 --> 20:34.700
father is saying that he was
unarmed. The police are saying
they believed he shot at

20:34.700 --> 20:38.671
them. So, that remains
to be squared away.

20:38.671 --> 20:43.776
Yamiche, I want to read you
something that one of the Saint
Louis aldermen, Antonio French,

20:43.776 --> 20:47.613
who has been very active in the
protest movement, he told a
reporter, he said, there is an
active

20:47.613 --> 20:51.784
protest group, and then he said
there are some people who are
just waiting for stuff

20:51.784 --> 20:55.387
to happen, just sitting back and
waiting for an opportunity to,
in his words, steal stuff

20:55.387 --> 20:57.022
and cause trouble.

20:57.022 --> 20:59.592
Is that what you're seeing?

20:59.592 --> 21:02.695
YAMICHE ALCINDOR: That's
what I'm observing too.

21:02.695 --> 21:08.100
I must say that the protesters,
the frequent protesters that I
have see them, they're
well-known

21:08.100 --> 21:11.604
faces. They know the police
officers. I have been covering
this story for more than

21:11.604 --> 21:15.508
a year. So, these protesters,
not only do they know each other
and not only do they

21:15.508 --> 21:18.677
how to act peaceably, not only
do they how to de-escalate
situations, but they also know

21:18.677 --> 21:21.213
police officers. And they
trust some of these officers.

21:21.213 --> 21:25.451
And they will walk up to them
and say, hey, things are getting
out of hand, or I saw an

21:25.451 --> 21:28.354
officer mace somebody, we really
didn't think that that was
appropriate.

21:28.354 --> 21:32.725
So, really, Ferguson has come a
long way since last year.
Protesters are really now in

21:32.725 --> 21:37.396
some ways, dare I say,
friendships with officers. So I
think that that's a different --
completely

21:37.396 --> 21:40.933
different relationship than
those people -- I don't know if
you would call agitators -- but

21:40.933 --> 21:45.704
there are people that are really
there not in any way connected
to the memory of Michael

21:45.704 --> 21:48.541
Brown, not any way connected to
the issues that the protesters
are talking about, but

21:48.541 --> 21:52.511
really they're just
there to cause trouble.

21:52.511 --> 21:56.215
And these are the people that
the protesters don't want to be
associated with. And,
yesterday,

21:56.215 --> 22:00.352
last night, I thought it was
really an important moment when
Chief Jon Belmar really said
during

22:00.352 --> 22:04.957
his press conference that these
are not protesters, these are
criminals.

22:04.957 --> 22:08.661
And that's a really big deal for
the protesters that come out
here every night and are
peaceful

22:08.661 --> 22:12.631
for hundreds of days, when you
have the police also
differentiating that person.

22:12.631 --> 22:16.569
JUDY WOODRUFF: Jon Belmar, of
course, being the Saint Louis
police chief.

22:16.569 --> 22:22.841
Just quickly, Yamiche, based on
what you know, what do you
expect to happen now?

22:22.841 --> 22:29.615
YAMICHE ALCINDOR: I really want
to say that I expect that people
will try to remain as

22:29.615 --> 22:34.753
peaceful as possible, that
people will really try to see --
when they see things escalating,

22:34.753 --> 22:38.490
try to alert the police. But
that's what they did last night.

22:38.490 --> 22:42.461
So, I'm really kind of cautious
to say what's going to happen
tonight because I want to

22:42.461 --> 22:45.898
say that things are going to go
calmly. But I know that there
is still -- even with the

22:45.898 --> 22:49.368
peaceful protesters, they don't
want to be told when to go home.
They're really into

22:49.368 --> 22:53.372
protesting. They're really into
observing their First Amendment
rights.

22:53.372 --> 22:56.508
And that's really important to
them, so people are really going
to be out there tonight.

22:56.508 --> 23:00.379
They are going to be out there
late. I imagine they will have a
really long night tonight

23:00.379 --> 23:04.083
and to stay out probably past
5:00 in the morning, because
that's what people do in

23:04.083 --> 23:06.952
Ferguson, because even when
they're protesting peacefully,
they don't go to sleep early at

23:06.952 --> 23:09.822
all. They stay out
very, very late.

23:09.822 --> 23:14.560
So I'm really worried though
about when the sun sets and
these people that don't want

23:14.560 --> 23:17.730
to be protesters, that don't
want to be peaceful, but these
people that really want to break

23:17.730 --> 23:21.367
into businesses, whether or not
they are going to be back
tonight. I have a scary feeling

23:21.367 --> 23:25.170
that they might be back tonight.
And I think that all journalists
and all people that are

23:25.170 --> 23:28.073
there are really just trying to
be as cautious as we can be to
really prepare ourselves for

23:28.073 --> 23:29.942
tonight.

23:29.942 --> 23:34.613
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right,
Yamiche Alcindor, reporter for
USA Today, we certainly hope

23:34.613 --> 23:41.954
nothing happens, but we know, as
you said, you will be there if
it is. Thank you.

23:41.954 --> 23:46.525
YAMICHE ALCINDOR: Thank you.

23:46.525 --> 23:53.465
GWEN IFILL: Stay with us.

23:53.465 --> 23:57.836
Coming up on the "NewsHour": an
American doctor tells the story
of his efforts to halt the

23:57.836 --> 24:03.008
spread of Ebola and his own
fight against the deadly virus;
and how parents who are

24:03.008 --> 24:07.913
not religious can teach their
children about God and faith.

24:07.913 --> 24:13.686
But first, the rollout of a
controversial reproductive
health law in the Philippines

24:13.686 --> 24:16.989
long resisted by the
Catholic Church there.

24:16.989 --> 24:19.792
Special correspondent Fred de
Sam Lazaro reports from Manila.

24:19.792 --> 24:24.196
A version of this story aired on
PBS' "Religion & Ethics
Newsweekly."

24:24.196 --> 24:30.202
FRED DE SAM LAZARO:
It's known as the baby

24:30.202 --> 24:34.139
factory. But unlike most
factories, the people who run
Manila's biggest public hospital

24:34.139 --> 24:36.975
wish this one were
less productive.

24:36.975 --> 24:42.548
The staff here at the maternity
ward say this is a fairly
typical, if not slightly quieter

24:42.548 --> 24:51.924
than usual day. Still, there
are 165 new mothers squeezed
into 127 beds. About 70

24:51.924 --> 24:56.662
babies are delivered every day.
Their mothers are treated free
of charge. They couldn't

24:56.662 --> 25:02.434
afford much anyway, with
household incomes of $5 a day,
often less.

25:02.434 --> 25:08.107
Most, like Irene Ocampo, who's
19, will tell you their
pregnancy was unplanned.

25:08.107 --> 25:12.077
IRENE OCAMPO, Mother (through
translator): I didn't know
anything about family planning

25:12.077 --> 25:15.914
before becoming pregnant.
That's why I had my baby. I
would have preferred to start

25:15.914 --> 25:20.018
having children at
20-plus, maybe 25.

25:20.018 --> 25:26.058
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: The
hospital recently added a new
service that could help her
better

25:26.058 --> 25:29.962
control when or even whether
to have more children.

25:29.962 --> 25:32.297
IRENE OCAMPO (through
translator): I want to have
three to five years between
them.

25:38.737 --> 25:43.976
in congress and court. It
requires public health
facilities to offer free
contraceptive

25:43.976 --> 25:48.414
services. These have long been
legally available in private
clinics, which poor patients
like

25:48.414 --> 25:51.283
these women could never afford.

25:51.283 --> 25:55.754
DR. SYLVIA DE LA PAZ,
Philippines: We want all
pregnancies should be wanted and
should

25:55.754 --> 25:59.491
end in a healthy
baby and mother.

25:59.491 --> 26:04.263
FRED DE SAM LAZARO:
Obstetrician Sylvia De La Paz
has worked in these wards for 22

26:04.263 --> 26:08.200
years. In that time, she says,
most patients have seen their
living conditions go from

26:08.200 --> 26:10.602
poor to poorer.

26:10.602 --> 26:15.073
DR. SYLVIA DE LA PAZ: Before,
there used to be street
children. Now you see street

26:15.073 --> 26:18.877
families. They sleep in the
streets. They have no homes.

26:18.877 --> 26:23.649
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Most
disturbing, she says, has been a
spike in teen pregnancies:

26:23.649 --> 26:27.686
up 50 percent in the country in
the last decade, more than
double in this hospital.

26:27.686 --> 26:29.655
Why do you think that is?

26:29.655 --> 26:34.526
DR. SYLVIA DE LA PAZ: I think
it's also exposure to early
sexual encounters. The

26:34.526 --> 26:47.306
age is now, I think, 12 to 14,
where, before, it used to 16 to
18. It's slid down now.

26:47.306 --> 26:49.942
ANGEL, Philippines (through
translator): I had no idea that
young people like me could

26:49.942 --> 26:52.144
have family planning.

26:52.144 --> 26:56.682
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Angel came
to this clinic run by a
nonprofit group to be fitted
with

26:56.682 --> 27:01.153
a contraceptive implant. Like
most teenagers who come here,
she only learned of this service

27:01.153 --> 27:04.890
after becoming pregnant at 14.

27:04.890 --> 27:09.561
ANGEL (through translator): I
wanted to finish my studies to
become a teacher. Becoming

27:09.561 --> 27:12.231
pregnant broke my dreams.

27:12.231 --> 27:16.201
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Some
proponents of the new
reproductive health law say an
entire

27:16.201 --> 27:21.840
nation's dream has been broken
by its failure to control
population growth.

27:21.840 --> 27:26.979
For instance, the Philippines
and neighboring Thailand once
has similar poverty levels,

27:26.979 --> 27:32.518
but Thailand cut its population
growth rate substantially in
recent decades, the result,

27:32.518 --> 27:37.589
Thais are far better off
economically, says Dr. Esparanza
Cabral, a former Philippine

27:37.589 --> 27:41.059
health minister and one of the
architects of the new law.

27:41.059 --> 27:44.363
DR. ESPARANZA CABRAL, Former
Health Minister: We know that
there is a big correlation

27:44.363 --> 27:51.670
between number of children and
poverty incidents. So the less
number of children you have,

27:51.670 --> 27:58.710
the lesser are your chances that
your family is poor. So that is
one aspect. And we

27:58.710 --> 28:04.049
can see this not just a family
basis, but on a countrywide
basis.

28:04.049 --> 28:08.186
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Father Joel
Jason is a spokesman for the
Catholic Archdiocese of

28:08.186 --> 28:12.724
Manila. He argues people are an
economic asset. He says they
have been poorly served

28:12.724 --> 28:15.160
by their government.

28:15.160 --> 28:20.265
REV. JOEL JASON, Archdiocese of
Manila: Give people job
opportunities, give children
education,

28:20.265 --> 28:26.605
and then you bring them out of
poverty. Just giving them
condoms and contraceptives will

28:26.605 --> 28:31.977
not automatically draw
them out of poverty.

28:31.977 --> 28:37.749
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: The church
has long been a huge influence
in this predominantly

28:37.749 --> 28:44.122
Catholic nation, its moral
teachings imprinted not just in
liturgy, but also in law.

28:44.122 --> 28:49.194
The Philippine constitution,
updated in 1987, says that the
state shall equally protect

28:49.194 --> 28:54.933
the mother and the unborn from
conception, and that's the basis
of opposition to the

28:54.933 --> 28:58.971
reproductive health law.
Opponents argue that just about
all methods of artificial

28:58.971 --> 29:03.342
contraception can
lead to abortion.

29:03.342 --> 29:08.380
Despite church opposition, the
court upheld most of the new
law, directing the country's

29:08.380 --> 29:15.654
food and drug administration to
approve non-abortion-causing
contraceptives. But the fight
hasn't ended.

29:15.654 --> 29:21.026
Some opponents plans to go back
to court. They argue the
methods now approved, like

29:21.026 --> 29:26.965
injectables or implants, pills
and IUDs, make the uterus
hostile to implantation, that
is,

29:26.965 --> 29:31.770
they prevent an embryo, which is
legally protected, from
attaching to the womb.

29:31.770 --> 29:36.041
Maria Noche is an attorney with
the group Alliance for the
Family.

29:36.041 --> 29:38.410
MARIA CONCEPCION NOCHE, Alliance
for the Family: All the
contraceptives that have been
registered

29:38.410 --> 29:43.415
right now, per our studies,
are all abortifacient.

29:43.415 --> 29:48.553
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: That is,
using them can lead to abortion.

29:48.553 --> 29:53.025
Father Jason draws a distinction
between contraception and family
planning, for which the church

29:53.025 --> 29:55.994
has no problem, he says.

29:55.994 --> 30:02.034
REV. JOEL JASON: You will not
find any single document,
present or in the past, that the

30:02.034 --> 30:06.071
church says women should have as
many children as they can
possibly bear.

30:06.071 --> 30:10.108
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: In fact,
Pope Francis drew worldwide
attention after recently
visiting

30:10.108 --> 30:14.713
the Philippines when he said
Catholics need not breed like
rabbits.

30:14.713 --> 30:20.385
But the pontiff reiterated that
the only acceptable birth
control method is natural family
planning,

30:20.385 --> 30:25.991
or NFP, where couples abstain
from sex on days when the woman
is fertile. Jason says

30:25.991 --> 30:30.028
artificial methods are a
symbol of a moral decay.

30:30.028 --> 30:35.867
REV. JOEL JASON: Why did we
invent contraceptives? Not
because NFP doesn't work, but
because

30:35.867 --> 30:42.340
we do not want to say no. And
that is why we are actually
slowly losing our sense of

30:42.340 --> 30:45.477
what sexuality
really is all about.

30:45.477 --> 30:51.850
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Back in the
maternity ward, Blessy Padua, a
laundry assistant who

30:51.850 --> 30:56.855
did go to high school, says she
and her husband did try what she
calls the calendar method,

30:56.855 --> 30:59.391
without success.

30:59.391 --> 31:03.562
BLESSY PADUA, Philippines
(through translator): I am
Catholic, and I am aware the
Church

31:03.562 --> 31:09.334
does not approve of family
planning, that God said go and
multiply. But at the same

31:09.334 --> 31:13.271
time, I already have a lot of
kids. I had to stop getting
pregnant.

31:13.271 --> 31:17.476
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: After
delivering her seventh child,
34-year-old Padua opted to

31:17.476 --> 31:20.445
be sterilized.

31:20.445 --> 31:25.617
Obstetrician De La Paz says, for
many women here, especially
those younger and unmarried,

31:25.617 --> 31:29.788
natural family planning is not a
good choice or a choice at all.

31:29.788 --> 31:33.925
DR. SYLVIA DE LA PAZ: Yes, a
lot of them have challenges with
their partners, who have

31:33.925 --> 31:38.630
issues with alcoholism, no job,
or inadequate income, so...

31:38.630 --> 31:44.136
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: How many of
them are married, would you
guess?

31:44.136 --> 31:48.707
DR. SYLVIA DE LA PAZ:
The majority not.

31:48.707 --> 31:53.545
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: One year
since implementation of the new
law began, she says most urban

31:53.545 --> 31:58.550
women now have access to family
planning services. About a
third of Philippine women still

31:58.550 --> 32:03.855
lack such access, most in rural
areas of this sprawling
archipelago.

32:03.855 --> 32:08.093
For the "PBS NewsHour," this is
Fred de Sam Lazaro in the
Philippines.

32:08.093 --> 32:11.930
GWEN IFILL: Fred's reporting is
a partnership with the
Under-Told Stories Project at
Saint

32:11.930 --> 32:19.905
Mary's University in Minnesota.

32:19.905 --> 32:32.551
JUDY WOODRUFF: Next: the
medical doctor who was airlifted
from Liberia to the U.S.

32:32.551 --> 32:37.255
one year ago this month after he
contracted Ebola while treating
patients in West Africa.

